A R T I C L E  I N F O   
Keywords: 
Glucagon-like peptide-1 
Incretins 
Diabetes mellitus 
Cognition 
Memory 
Alzheimer’s disease 
A B S T R A C T   
Glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) receptor agonists are a class of antidiabetic drugs that improve the glycaemia 
via several molecular pathways. Recent evidence suggest that they also have additional effects modulating 
pathophysiologic pathways included in cognitive disorders. Since some forms of cognitive dysfunction such as 
Alzheimer’s disease are more common among diabetic patients than in the normal population, antidiabetic drugs 
that have neuroprotective effects affording protection for cognitive disorders would be of benefit. Therefore, we 
reviewed the pharmacologic effects of GLP-1 analogues and found that they may have the additional benefit of 
improving cognitive performance via at least eight molecular mechanisms.   
1. Introduction 
The global prevalence of diabetes mellitus (DM) is growing rapidly 
[1] with the result of increased morbidity and mortality from diabetic 
complications [2]. Diabetic complications are a major cause of disabil­
ities with an increasing economic healthcare burden [2,3]. It has been 
shown that people with poor glycemic control are at higher risk of tissue 
dysfunction, age-related disorders as well as neuronal complications and 
cognitive problems compared to those without diabetes [3]. Cognitive 
disorders in older people are a major issue in global health that markedly 
impairs quality of life, especially in those with diabetes [3–5]. Epide­
miological studies have shown that DM predicts most neuronal injuries 
as dementia and cognitive impairment and increases the risk of these 
complications [6]. They also suggested that effective anti-diabetic 
agents are promising therapeutic interventions to prevent neuronal 
impairment by suppressing the underlying pathophysiologic pathways 
[6–9]. 
Glucagon-like peptide-1 receptor agonists (GLP-1RA) are a newly 
introduced class of antidiabetic drugs that improve glycemic control via 
several molecular pathways [10,11]. These pharmacologic agents are 
effective hypoglycemic drugs that reduce blood glucose via glucose- 
dependent insulin secretion and by glucagon suppression [11]. There 
is increasing data suggesting that they also have extra-pancreatic effects, 
which may enable them to modulate other physiological or pathological 
molecular mechanisms involved in diabetic complications, as well in 
cognitive impairment [8,11,12]. GLP-1 and its analogues can cross the 
blood brain barrier (BBB) and therefore are able to affect central nervous 
system functions such as cognition and neuroprotection [13,14]. How­
ever, the exact molecular pathways mediating neuroprotective roles of 
GLP-1RAs are not clear. In the current study we aimed to understand the 
molecular pathways by which GLP-1RAs may protect against cognitive 
dysfunction and dementia. 
2. Incretin-based antidiabetic drugs 
Incretins are a group of intestinal metabolic peptides included of 
GLP-1 and GIP (gastric inhibitory peptide), which decrease postprandial 
glycaemia via several pathways such as glucagon inhibition, insulin 
secretion, delayed the gastric emptying, appetite suppression, reduced 
intestinal nutrient absorption, improvement of lipid metabolism, and 
