2
promoting pancreatic β-cell efficiency [15–19]. GLP-1 is an endogenous 
hormone with 30 amino acids derived from pre-proglucagon molecule in 
the enteroendocrine L-cells of the gastrointestinal tract [20]. GLP-1RA 
are a newly introduced class of antidiabetic drugs that have their hy­
poglycemic effects by mimicking the incretin hormones through in­
duction of GLP-1 receptor activity [15,21]. The GLP-1 receptor (R) is a 
member of G-protein coupled receptors and are principally located on 
surfaces of pancreatic β-cells [17]. GLP-1R activation induces cAMP 
(cyclic adenosine monophosphate) production followed by cellular de­
polarization and insulin secretion from the pancreatic β-cells [17,22]. 
GLP-1 is metabolized by the proteolytic activity of the ubiquitously 
expressed dipeptidyl peptdase-4 (DPP-4) enzyme; therefore, DPP-4 in­
hibitors have a hypoglycemic effect by increasing the active levels of 
endogenous GLP-1 [23,24]. 
3. GLP-1RA and cognition 
GLP-1 analogues are potent hypoglycemic agents lowering blood 
glucose [25], but some studies have shown that they have an additional 
beneficial effect in diabetic subjects by improving the cognitive 
dysfunction [26]. Although the exact mediated molecular mechanisms 
are unclear, in the following sections we present the likely involved 
pathways (Fig. 1, Table 1). 
3.1. Neuroinflammation 
Inflammatory events in neuronal structures or neuroinflammation 
have essential roles in cognitive impairment and memory deficits 
especially in diabetic patients [27,28]. This deleterious mechanism 
negatively impacts on neuronal function and physiologic efficiency of 
neuronal structures and is closely involved in the pathophysiology of 
different forms of cognitive impairment and memory loss in diabetic and 
non-diabetic patients [28–30]. Inflammatory responses markedly 
reduce nerve conduction velocity, axonal excitability and synaptic ef­
ficiency leading to a lower rate of signal transduction and neuronal 
integrity [31–33]. Experimental and clinical models of Alzheimer’s 
disease (AD) and cognitive impairments are commonly accompanied 
with neuroinflammation [34]. Therefore, inhibition or suppressing the 
inflammatory response is a promising target in patients with cognitive 
complications to enhance cognitive function [32]. 
There are data indicating the GLP-1 receptor mimetics provide anti- 
inflammatory effects in neuronal structures [11,35,36]. Yoon et al. 
(2020) found that GLP-1 improves glial morphology and neurite 
complexity via suppressing tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-α) 
dependent inflammation in cultured BV-2 microglia [35]. McClean et al. 
(2014) demonstrated that liraglutide, a GLP1R agonist, reversed 
neuroinflammation-induced memory deficits by reducing β-amyloid 
(Aβ) plaques and improving neural integrity in aged APP/PS1 mice [37]. 
In addition, Diz-Chaves and coworkers (2018) established that liraglu­
tide improved glial morphology and hippocampal function through 
suppression of inflammatory responses in rats [38]. Moreover, Cui et al. 
(2020) reported that exendin-4, a GLP-1RA, improved cognitive func­
tions via lowering neuroinflammatory events in the hippocampus of rats 
[39]. It has been shown that GLP-1 analogues can provide anti- 
inflammatory effects via the gut-brain axis [40,41], and they can 
modulate microbiome homeostasis and ameliorate systemic inflamma­
tory responses via the gut-brain connections [42]. These data strongly 
suggest that GLP-1RAs are able to attenuate neuroinflammation-induced 
cognitive impairment and thereby, could be promising therapeutic 
agents to prevent memory loss in diabetes [20]. 
3.2. Oxidative damage 
Oxidative stress referred to an imbalance between free radicals and 
the cellular anti-oxidant defense system in favor of the formation of free 
radicals [43]. This deleterious event is closely involved in many com­
plications as well as neuronal problems and cognitive dysfunction 
[8,9,44]. It has been previously demonstrated that oxidative stress 
predicts cognitive impairment in the healthy individuals [45]. In addi­
tion, it is involved in both age-related or diabetes-induced neuronal 
dysfunction and hippocampal derangement in patients with cognitive 
and memory impairment [46–48]. Thus, readjusting the redox state is an 
important target in these patients [45]. 
There is good data to suggest that GLP-1R induction provides anti- 
oxidative effects in a variety of tissues as well as in CNS [49–51]. 
They can prevent oxidative damage via either lowering the amount of 
free radical generation or potentiation of antioxidative defense systems 
to increase the antioxidant capacity of the cells [52–54]. Li et al. (2016) 
found that exendin-4 improved cognitive functions via suppressing 
