3
oxidative stress through Akt1-eNOS2 signaling pathway in diabetes 
conditions [49]. Lennox and colleagues (2014) demonstrated that the 
GLP-1 analogue of Val8 protected against oxidative stress induced 
cognitive dysfunction in diabetic mice [55]. They found that GLP-1R 
induction decreased hippocampal levels of 8-oxoguanine as a marker 
of oxidative stress and improved LTP3 related memory in treated dia­
betic animals [55]. Chen and coworkers (2014) provided evidence 
showing GLP-1 inhibits hippocampal neuronal apoptosis [56]. 
Likewise, Yang and colleagues (2018) established that liraglutide has 
antioxidative effects via mTOR4 activation and AMPK5 and PI3K6/Akt 
signaling pathways in diabetic rats [57]. Duarte and coworkers recently 
provided further evidence implying neuroprotective effects of liraglu­
tide are mainly related to its antioxidative properties in diabetic con­
ditions [58]. Moreover, Day et al. (2019) reported that a metabolite of 
GLP-1, GLP-1 (9-36), has therapeutic effects improving cognitive func­
tion through lowering the oxidative stress in animals with Down’s 
syndrome [59]. These data suggest that GLP-1R analogues are able to 
improve cognitive and learning abilities via attenuating the oxidative 
damage in neuronal networks. 
3.3. Insulin signaling pathway 
Physiological functions of neurons and neuronal structures are 
affected by insulin and its downstream intracellular signaling [60,61], 
with effects on metabolic pathways and energy balance in the neurons 
[62]. In addition, it has regulatory roles on physiological functions/ 
properties of the neurons and its cellular signaling is required for normal 
activity of the neurons [63,64]. Insulin is the main effective agent in 
many physiological processes in the CNS such as cognition, memory, 
learning and recall [64,65]. Patients with decreased insulin level/ac­
tivity are at higher risk of AD, Parkinson’s disease (PD), hippocampal 
atrophy, dis-attention as well as neurodegenerative disorders [65–67]. 
These patients mostly have impaired glucose utilization in the CNS and 
dysregulation of brain insulin and IGF-17 signaling leading to insulin 
resistance, disturbed metabolism and pathological changes in the 
neuronal structures [20,68,69]. 
Insulin receptors in the CNS provide neuroprotective effects and 
their activity are important in brain function [70]. It has been suggested 
that impaired insulin signaling has a direct relationship with memory 
loss and cognitive disorders [69]. In addition, AD patients with cognitive 
problems and memory deficit have some degrees of insulin resistance in 
their neuronal structures and CNS [36,68]. Moreover, synaptogenesis 
and synaptic plasticity in CNS; which are molecular events important in 
learning and memory; are closely under the influence of insulin 
[68,71,72], thus, insulin plays major roles in cognition and memory 
[72]. 
GLP-1 analogues have effects on insulin secretion [73] and have 
positive modulatory effects on intracellular insulin signaling [73–75]. 
Moreover, they may provide compensatory effects for impaired insulin 
and insulin-like growth factors to inducing cellular proliferation [75]. 
Therefore, they could indirectly improve cognitive functions in patients 
with insulin dependent cognitive problems [74,76]. Gumuslu et al. 
(2016) found that exenatide was able to improve cognitive performance 
via improving insulin signal transduction in diabetic mice [77]. Shi and 
colleagues (2017) demonstrated that the GLP-1R agonist of DA-JC4 
improved memory and cognition via promoting insulin signaling in 
diabetic animals [74]. They found that the GLP-1 analogue decreased 
phospho-IRS1Ser1101 levels and up-regulated phospho-AktSer473 leading 
to improved insulin signaling in the brain [74]. Moreover, Batista and 
coworkers (2018) revealed that liraglutide exerts neuroprotective ef­
fects via promoting insulin signal transduction pathways [78]. They 
found that the GLP-1 analogue upregulate brain insulin receptors lead­
ing to improved cognitive functions in a primate model of AD [78]. 
These data strongly suggest that incretins are able to improve cognitive 
performance, at least partially via mimicking and promoting insulin 
signaling [76]; however, more clinical studies are required. 
3.4. Neuroapoptosis 
Apoptosis is a biologic event of programmed cell death and involved 
in many physiological processes such as growth, maturation and 
migration [79]. It is a highly controlled cellular process that occurs 
under the influence of different stimuli and factors and is an essential 
event in the cell cycle [79]. However, in uncontrolled and pathologic 
states, it can result in histological injury in differing tissues as well as in 
neuronal structures [79]. It has been confirmed that neuroapoptosis is 
included in the pathophysiology of neuronal disorders and neuropathies 
and is involved in most forms of cognitive problems and memory loss 
[80,81]. Thus, many pharmacologic agents have been tested in recent 
years to prevent this deleterious mechanism in neurons in order to 
improving cognitive and memory abilities [82–84]. 
There is direct evidence suggesting that incretins have effective anti- 
apoptotic effects [85]. Incretins are able to cross BBB and directly reduce 
neuronal apoptosis [85]. Also, they can suppress upstream pathophysi­
ological pathways stimulating apoptosis such as oxidative stress and 
inflammation [86]. Kimura and coworkers (2009) found that GLP-1 
suppressed apoptotic cellular death via PI3K/Akt/mTOR/GCLc8/redox 
signaling pathway in cultured PC129 cells [85]. Moreover, Biswas et al. 
(2008) have reported that GLP-1 prevented BIM10 dependent apoptosis 
in cultured neuronal PC12 cells [87]. They concluded that incretins 
protect neuronal structures via damping apoptotic death [87]. Chen 
et al. (2016) have reported that GLP-1R induction down-regulated pro- 
apoptotic elements such as caspase-3, caspase-9, Bax and Bcl-2 in neu­
rons of mice [88]. 
Mohiuddin and coworkers (2019) have demonstrated that, exendin- 
4 have protective effects against neuropathy by attenuating apoptotic 
cellular death and decreasing cell counts [89]. In addition, Shi and co­
workers (2017) have showed that dual incretins agonist of DA-JC4 im­
proves cognitive function by inhibiting neuronal apoptosis [74]. They 
found that DA-JC4 lowers the neuroapoptotic events by decreasing BAX 
to BCL2 ratio in rats [74]. Furthermore, Yang et al. (2018) reported that 
liraglutide had beneficial effects improving cognition and memory by 
damping neuronal apoptosis via down-regulating Beclin-1 and LC-311 II 
in rats [57]. Although we have no direct clinical evidence, these animal 
studies strongly suggest a neuroprotective effect of incretins leading to 
an improvement of cognitive functions that may be associated with 
lowering the neuroapoptosis in related neuronal areas. 
3.5. Anti-toxicity 
Neurotoxicity is a pathologic state increasing the risk of neurode­
generative disorders as well as cognitive dysfunction [90]. This term 
refers to any injury to the neuronal structures caused by exposure to 
natural or synthetic toxins that disturb normal functions of the neurons 
[90]. There is data to suggest that incretins have anti-toxicity effects 
[91,92] such as a reduction in neuronal toxicity via control of calcium 
influx into the neurons, which in turn decreases the toxic effects of 
