4
glutamate exposure [91]. In addition, they are able to attenuate exci­
totoxic effects of glutamate exposure in cultured hippocampal neurons 
[92] and they can protect neurons against hyperglycemia dependent 
toxicity [93]. It has been suggested that the GLP-1 analogue exenatide 
increases cell survival by lowering this glucotoxicity [93]. Protection 
against these agents of toxicity, incretins may potentially reflect in 
cognitive improvement though further investigation is required. 
3.6. β-amyloid and Tau protein aggregation/deposition 
Most types of memory loss or cognitive impairment are related to 
increased deposition or aggregation of toxic proteins such as Aβ or tau 
proteins [94,95]. Aβ is a toxic peptide consisting 36–43 amino acids 
produced from the amyloid precursor protein (APP) and its plaques in 
brain cortical area is recognized as the main hallmark of AD [96]. Tau 
proteins are a group of structural proteins with physiological function 
especially in microtubules, but in case of hyperphosphorylation becomes 
toxic insoluble aggregated proteins involved in pathophysiology of AD 
and PD [97]. Patients with AD are commonly recognized by higher 
density of Aβ plaques or more tau proteins in area related to memory and 
cognition [96]. Therefore, prevention or amelioration of the rate of Aβ 
or tau protein deposition is a major focus in dementia and cognitive 
disorders [97–99]. 
There is evidence that incretins may potentially modify this patho­
logical process [58,100–102]. GLP-1 mimetics decrease endogenous Aβ 
production [100] and Perry and colleagues showed that GLP-1 can 
reduce APP levels and decrease Aβ generation in cultured hippocampal 
cells [100]. Li and coworkers (2010) reported that exendin-4 reduced 
both Aβ and tau protein levels in brain of diabetic mice [103]. Cai et al. 
(2014) demonstrated that GLP-1R induction with lixisenatide reversed 
Aβ related spatial memory and cognitive dysfunction via PI3K-Akt- 
GSK3b12 pathways [104], with a decrease in Aβ plaque levels and 
induced synaptic plasticity in treated animals [104]. Hansen et al. 
(2016) demonstrated that liraglutide reduced tau protein phosphoryla­
tion that resulted in improved motor function in mice [105]. 
McClean and coworkers in 2014 established that liraglutide 
decreased Aβ levels in the brains of aged mice [37], with liraglutide 
reversing memory impairment by lowering the Aβ levels in brain tissue 
in an experimental model of AD [37]. Chen et al. (2014) reported that 
GLP-1 inhibited tau protein phosphorylation in hippocampal neurons 
[56] in accord with findings from Li et al. (2012) who reported the same 
results stating VAL8 reduced tau protein levels and reduced its phos­
phorylation leading to improved spatial memory in the rat brain [106]. 
Furthermore, Duarte et al. (2020) demonstrated that female mice 
treated with liraglutide lowered cortical Aβ accumulation in the brain 
accompanied with partial improvement in cognitive function [58]. 
These data suggest that lowering the Aβ or tau proteins accumulation is a 
potential benefit from incretin therapy to improve cognitive and mem­
ory function [107]. 
3.7. Neurogenesis and synaptic plasticity 
In addition to being a metabolic peptide, GLP-1 is a growth factor 
that may induce neurite growth by up-regulating genes involved in 
neurogenesis [108–110]. It can effectively induce distinct DNA pro­
moters and stimulate proliferation and biogenesis of cells as well as 
neurons [108–110]. Lennox et al. in 2014 showed that a GLP-1 analogue 
upregulated essential proteins in the hippocampus such as mTOR, 
VEGF,13 NTRK214 and SIRT115 in diabetic mice [55]. They have 
demonstrated that Val8 promoted neurogenesis in hippocampal tissues 
of treated animals leading to better cognitive function [55]. Gumuslu 
et al. (2016) reported that exenatide has potent neurotrophic effects and 
promotes neurogenesis in diabetic conditions [77]. They established 
that exenatide upregulated CREB16 and BDNF17 genes in the hippo­
campus leading to improved cognitive function in treated diabetic ani­
mals [77]. Day and colleagues reported that the GLP-1 (9–36) 
metabolite of GLP-1 has marked effects on neurogenesis as it improved 
dendritic spine morphology and increased density of mature spines in an 
animal model of down syndrome [59]. Interestingly, they have shown 
that these molecular alterations in neuronal structures translated into 
functional changes and improved cognitive performance in these ani­
mals [59]. 
There are also evidence of incretins having a positive modulatory 
effects on synaptic plasticity [111]. McClean and coworkers (2010) re­
ported that liraglutide increased synaptic transmission and potentiated 
LTP in CA1 layer of hippocampus [111]. They showed that these neu­
romodulatory effects of liraglutide were accompanied with improved 
cognitive performance [111]. Abbas and colleagues in 2009 found that 
GLP-1R knockout in diabetic mice was associated with severely 
impaired LTP in area CA1 and concluded that, GLP-1 had regulatory 
effects on synaptic plasticity and memory formation [112]. Ji et al. 
(2016) suggested that the GLP-1R agonist of DA-JC1 reversed cognitive 
impairment via BDNF-dependent neurogenesis in an animal model of PD 
[113]. Thus, it seems that, GLP-1 analogues have potent neurotrophic 
effects enabling them to promoting neurogenesis and synaptic trans­
mission [55,59,114]. Therefore, incretins may improve cognitive ability 
in part via induction of neurogenesis, synaptogenesis and LTP forma­
tion/potentiation [114]. 
3.8. Direct central effects 
In addition to peripheral tissues, GLP-1Rs are widely distributed in 
the central nervous system (CNS) [62,115]. They are expressed in 
different area of the CNS such as the arcuate nucleus, paraventricular 
nucleus, olfactory bulb, proopiomelanocortin (POMC) neurons and 
ventral medial hypothalamic nucleus, thalamus, caudate-putamen, 
globus pallidus, pyramidal neurons in the hippocampus and 
neocortex, and purkinje cells in the cerebellum as well as in the brain 
stem [17,55,62,115–118]. There is evidence of the existence of GLP-1 
producing neurons [17,62,116]. Moreover, peripherally derived GLP-1 
may have central effects by passing through the BBB and activating 
brain GLP-1Rs [115]. Thus, it seems that GLP-1 mimetics play essential 
roles in energy homeostasis and normal functions of neuronal structures 
[55,116]. Evidence indicates that GLP-1 mimetics are involved in 
memory formation and cognitive abilities [36,119]. Also, animals who 
overexpressed GLP-1Rs have increased learning capacity compared to 
wild type [120]. This suggests that GLP-1 analogues are able to improve 
cognitive functions via direct central effects, although clarification of 
this is needed (Table 1). 
4. Possible interactions 
Although we have summarized the main molecular mechanisms that 
are involved through eight separate cellular pathways, is should be 
noted that it is likely that these may have additional complex synergistic 
interactions that have not yet been described in this new field of 
research. For example, it was shown that oxidative stress or inflamma­
tory responses are themselves potent inducers of apoptotic events 
[121,122]; moreover, they have negative effects on cellular signaling of 
insulin peptide [123–125]. There is increasing evidence reporting that 
oxidative stress or inflammatory responses can promote neurotoxicity 
and reduce the neurogenesis processes and thereby interrupt physiologic 
