5
growth of neuronal structures [9,126,127]. It is likely that these in­
teractions may also occur with the molecular pathways discussed here. 
Hence, whilst GLP-1 analogues have potent neuromodulatory effects via 
several interacted molecular mechanisms, not all of these interactions 
have not been fully identified and further clarification is required. 
5. Clinical evidence 
There are few clinical studies showing that GLP-1 mimetics improve 
cognitive function [128]. Wu et al. (2018) reported that serum levels of 
GLP-1 was closely correlated to cognitive performance in diabetic pa­
tients [128]. They found that lower serum levels of GLP-1 may be 
involved in the pathogenesis of cognitive impairment [128]. A more 
recent study in 2020 reported that liraglutide improved memory and 
cognition and slowed cognitive impairment in prediabetic and diabetic 
patients [129]. However, there are some adverse reports [130], and 
clarification is needed from further clinical studies [131] (Table 2). 
6. Conclusion 
GLP-1 mimetics could have dual benefits in patients with type 2 
diabetes. In addition to improved glycemic control there is compelling 
experimental evidence to suggest that they may be associated with 
improved cognitive impairment in diabetes. Incretins can positively 
modulate cognitive function via at least eight molecular and cellular 
pathways including a reduction in oxidative damage, inflammation, 
neuroapoptosis, and Aβ or tau protein aggregation, or by improvements 
in neurogenesis and synaptic plasticity, neurotoxicity, and insulin signal 
transduction. Using one effective pleiotropic medication to address 
diabetes mellitus and related complications could result in a reduction in 
healthcare costs and a reduction in the medication burden. Further 
clinical evidence is needed to establish the impact of analogues on 
cognitive and memory functions in diabetic patients. 
